    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nI just performed and fresh build of neovim `v0.11.6` and when running `make test` I get a bunch of test failures like\n```\nFAILED   test/functional/lua/fs_spec.lua @ 424: vim.fs root() returns CWD (absolute path) for buffers with non-empty 'buftype'\ntest/functional/lua/fs_spec.lua:429: Expected objects to be the same.\nPassed in:\n(string) '/Data/home/robert/Documents/Git/neovim'\nExpected:\n(string) '/home/robert/Documents/Git/neovim'\n\nstack traceback:\n        test/functional/lua/fs_spec.lua:429: in function <test/functional/lua/fs_spec.lua:424>\n\nFAILED   test/functional/lua/fs_spec.lua @ 435: vim.fs root() returns CWD (absolute path) if no match is found\ntest/functional/lua/fs_spec.lua:437: Expected objects to be the same.\nPassed in:\n(string) '/Data/home/robert/Documents/Git/neovim'\nExpected:\n(string) '/home/robert/Documents/Git/neovim'\n\nstack traceback:\n        test/functional/lua/fs_spec.lua:437: in function <test/functional/lua/fs_spec.lua:435>\n```\n\nThe thing is, the expected and actual paths are actually the same, because I have `/home/robert/Documents` symlinked to `/Data/home/robert/Documents` (which lives on a separate hard drive).\n\nHence, these tests should perform path normalization (including resolving symlinks) before comparing paths.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nRun `make test` while having the repo root under a path that contains a symlink\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThose tests should pass\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.11.6\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNot tested - but I don't think this would apply to Vim in the first place\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux (based on Ubuntu 24.04)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nKonsole 25.12.3\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nEmpty\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
